description:
LOW: Webview panel uses retainContextWhenHidden: true which keeps the entire webview in memory even when not visible.

Location: extension.ts:408

Root cause: Over-aggressive resource retention. For a simple detail panel that can be cheaply regenerated, this is unnecessary overhead.

Fix: Remove the option (defaults to false):
```typescript
const panel = vscode.window.createWebviewPanel(
  'beadsxDetail',
  \`Issue: \${issue.id}\`,
  vscode.ViewColumn.One,
  {
    enableScripts: true,
    // Remove retainContextWhenHidden - not needed for static content
  },
);
```

LOW: The lastClickedItem global state persists across VS Code window reloads.

Location: extension.ts:13-14

Root cause: Global mutable state without cleanup mechanism. While unlikely to cause real issues (timestamps would be stale), it violates isolation principles.

Fix: Move state into activation context or reset on deactivate:
```typescript
export function activate(context: vscode.ExtensionContext) {
  let lastClickedItem = { id: '', timestamp: 0 };
  // ... use in command handler
}
```

MEDIUM: vscode.workspace.getConfiguration('beadsx') called for every tree item rendered.

Location: beadsTreeDataProvider.ts:136-137, 173

Root cause: No configuration caching. For a list of 100 issues, this calls getConfiguration 200+ times per refresh.

Fix: Cache configuration and refresh on config change:
```typescript
private cachedConfig = {
  autoExpand: true,
  shortIds: false,
};

constructor(...) {
  this.refreshConfig();
}

private refreshConfig(): void {
  const config = vscode.workspace.getConfiguration('beadsx');
  this.cachedConfig.autoExpand = config.get('autoExpandOpen', true);
  this.cachedConfig.shortIds = config.get('shortIds', false);
}
```

MEDIUM: In beadsService.ts:153-155, config value is used without validation. Negative/zero values would break filtering silently. Users can manually edit settings.json with invalid values.

Fix: Add runtime validation with clamping:
```typescript
let recentWindowHours = config.get<number>('recentWindowHours', 1);
if (typeof recentWindowHours !== 'number' || Number.isNaN(recentWindowHours)) {
  log(`Warning: Invalid recentWindowHours, using default 1 hour`);
  recentWindowHours = 1;
} else if (recentWindowHours < 0.1) {
  recentWindowHours = 0.1;
} else if (recentWindowHours > 168) {
  recentWindowHours = 168;
}
```

HIGH: execFileAsync calls to bd command have no timeout. If bd hangs (e.g., waiting for daemon), the extension will hang indefinitely.

Location: beadsService.ts:75, 136

Root cause: Missing defensive timeout configuration for child process execution.

Fix: Add timeout option to execFileAsync calls:
```typescript
const result = await execFileAsync(bdCmd, ['ready', '--json'], {
  cwd: workspaceRoot,
  timeout: 30000, // 30 second timeout
});
```

MEDIUM: Output channel created as module-level constant outside activate() function.

Location: extension.ts:345

Root cause: Module-level side effects violate VS Code extension best practices. Resources should be created in activate() and registered for disposal.

Current code:
```typescript
const outputChannel = vscode.window.createOutputChannel('BeadsX Extension');
```

Fix: Move creation into activate() and add to subscriptions:
```typescript
export function activate(context: vscode.ExtensionContext) {
  const outputChannel = vscode.window.createOutputChannel('BeadsX Extension');
  context.subscriptions.push(outputChannel);
  // ... rest of activation
}
```

LOW-MEDIUM: While execFile is safer than exec, the user-configurable commandPath is passed directly without validation.

Location: beadsService.ts:33-37

Root cause: User-configurable path passed directly to execFile. If a user (or malicious workspace settings) sets commandPath to something unexpected, it could cause issues.

Fix: Add path validation:
```typescript
function getBdCommand(): string {
  const config = vscode.workspace.getConfiguration('beadsx');
  const customPath = config.get<string>('commandPath', '');

  if (customPath) {
    // Basic validation - no shell metacharacters
    if (/[;&|<>\`\$]/.test(customPath)) {
      log('Warning: Invalid commandPath contains shell metacharacters, using default');
      return 'bd';
    }
    return customPath;
  }
  return 'bd';
}
```

LOW: The _onDidChangeTreeData and _onDidLoadData event emitters are not disposed.

Location: beadsTreeDataProvider.ts:8-13, 121-123

Root cause: Incomplete dispose implementation. EventEmitters should be disposed to clean up listeners.

Fix: Dispose emitters in dispose():
```typescript
dispose(): void {
  this.stopAutoReload();
  this._onDidChangeTreeData.dispose();
  this._onDidLoadData.dispose();
}
```

HIGH: In beadsService.ts:160, `new Date(issue.closed_at).getTime()` returns NaN for malformed dates. When comparing `NaN >= cutoffTime`, result is always false, silently excluding issues.

Fix: Validate parsed date and log warning when parsing fails:
```typescript
const closedDate = new Date(issue.closed_at);
const closedTime = closedDate.getTime();
if (Number.isNaN(closedTime)) {
  log(`Warning: Issue ${issue.id} has invalid closed_at: "${issue.closed_at}"`);
  return false;
}
return closedTime >= cutoffTime;
```

MEDIUM: Synchronous file system call on the main thread can block VS Code's UI.

Location: beadsService.ts:14-17

Root cause: fs.existsSync is synchronous and blocks the event loop. On slow filesystems (network drives, WSL), this can cause noticeable UI jank.

Fix: Use async version with caching:
```typescript
import { access } from 'node:fs/promises';

let beadsInitializedCache: Map<string, boolean> = new Map();

export async function isBeadsInitialized(workspaceRoot: string): Promise<boolean> {
  if (beadsInitializedCache.has(workspaceRoot)) {
    return beadsInitializedCache.get(workspaceRoot)!;
  }
  const beadsDir = path.join(workspaceRoot, '.beads');
  try {
    await access(beadsDir);
    beadsInitializedCache.set(workspaceRoot, true);
    return true;
  } catch {
    beadsInitializedCache.set(workspaceRoot, false);
    return false;
  }
}
```

IMPORTANT: The getChildren method creates a promise chain for loading issues but doesn't handle errors.

Location: beadsTreeDataProvider.ts:262-277

If an unhandled rejection occurs, VS Code may show generic error messages or the tree view may remain in an indeterminate state.

Fix: Add .catch() handler:
```typescript
.catch(error => {
  this.log(`Error loading issues: ${error}`);
  return [];
})
```

LOW: The escapeHtml and formatDate functions are defined inside getDetailHtml() and recreated on every HTML generation.

Location: extension.ts:17-31

Root cause: Function definitions in hot path create unnecessary garbage collection pressure.

Fix: Move to module level:
```typescript
const escapeHtml = (str: string) =>
  str
    .replace(/&/g, '&amp;')
    .replace(/</g, '&lt;')
    .replace(/>/g, '&gt;')
    .replace(/"/g, '&quot;')
    .replace(/'/g, '&#039;');

const formatDetailDate = (dateStr: string) => {
  try {
    return new Date(dateStr).toLocaleString();
  } catch {
    return dateStr;
  }
};
```
